ority Mother: Race, Disability, and Reproductive Exclusion in Asian American Families -- t12. “Can’t We All Just Get Along?” Public Opinion on Race in Los Angeles Twenty-Five Years after Rodney King -- tPart IV. New Epistemologies and Methodologies -- t13. Mana as Sacred Space: A Talanoa of Tongan American College Students in a Pacific Studies Learning Community Classroom -- t14. Unsettling the Settler Colonial Triptych: Visioning AlterNative Futures with Octavia E. Butler’s Wild Seed -- t15. Creating Intuitively: The Art and Flow of Intuitive Social Science -- t16. On the Margins of Sociology and Grounded in Chicana/o Latina/o Studies: Cross-Generational Reflections on (Un)Disciplining -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbout the Contributors -- tAbout the Editors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReimagines how race, ethnicity, imperialism, and colonialism can be central to social science researchand methodsThere is a growing consensus that the discipline of sociology and the social sciences broadly need to engage more thoroughly with the legacy and the present day of colonialism, Indigenous/settler colonialism, imperialism, and racial capitalism in the United States and globally. In Disciplinary Futures, a cross-section of scholars comes together to engage sociology and the social sciences by way of these paradigms, particularly from the influence of disciplines of American, Ethnic, and Indigenous Studies.With original essays from scholars such as Yến Lê Espiritu, Sunaina Maira, Hōkūlani K. Aikau, Salvador Vidal-Ortiz, Ben Carrington, Yvonne Sherwood, and Gilda L. Ochoa, among others, Disciplinary Futures offers concrete pathways for how the social sciences can expand from the limiting frameworks they traditionally use to study race and racism, namely: the black-white binary, the privileging of the nation-state, the fixation on the US mainland, the underappreciation of post- and settler-colonial studies, the liberal assumptions, and the limited conception of what constitutes data. In turn, the contributors reveal that sociology has many useful questions, methodologies, and approaches to offer scholars of American, Ethnic, and Indigenous Studies. Disciplinary Futuresis an important work, one which renders these disciplines more intellectually expansive and thus better able to tackle urgent issues of injustice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMinoritiesxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 0aRacial justicexStudy and teachingzUnited States. 0aRacismxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 0aSociologyxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aFilipino immigrants.  aH1B visa.  aIndigenous Justice.  aMauna Kea movement.  aMuslim ban.  aPacific and Oceania studies.  aSpanish imperialism.  aVietnamese refugees.  aWar on Terror.  aactivism.  adecolonization.  aforced migration.  agendered citizenship.  aimmigration law.  ainterdisciplinary.  amigration.  aneoliberalism.  apolicing.  apost-colonialism.  aracial capitalism.  arefugees.  asettler colonialism.  asmall businesses.  asurveillance.  ataro patents.  atransnationalism.  atribal nationhood.1 aAikau, Hōkūlani K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarrington, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDas Gupta, Monisha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDhingra, Pawan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDhingra, Pawan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aE. Enriquez, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEscudero, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo